      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "28a930b5_c0be7eb9",
      "file_path": "components/pm-subscription-handler/tests/test_network_function_filter.py",
      "patchset_number": 8,
      "line": 9,
      "message": "I'd recommend using parameterized for this, \nhttps://pypi.org/project/parameterized/\nit'll give you individual tests, rather than having a single test which is what this is doing.\nThe docs even give you an easy example on how you can have each test identify with a custom name.\nadditionally you can store the test data either as lists in the code base or external like it is now, up to yourself, but it's much better to have each test identify as a separate one.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 4023,
        "name": "Joseph O'Leary",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "joseph.o.leary@est.tech",
        "username": "JoeOLeary"
      },
      "updated": "2020-09-04 12:17:39.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "ea064f52_28e3f3fb",
      "file_path": "components/pm-subscription-handler/tests/test_network_function_filter.py",
      "patchset_number": 10,
      "line": 33,
      "message": "If you change the filter_test_data.json to just be an array rather than an object containing an array,\nthen you can use a custom function to read the contents, and generate parameters for the tests.\n\n\nsome food for thought:\n\n   def load_test_cases():\n        test_parameters = []\n        with open(os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), 'data/filter_test_data.json'), r) as test_data:\n            loaded_test_data = json.load(data)\n        for test in loaded_test_data:\n            params = [value for key, value in test.items()]\n            test_parameters.append(params)\n        return test_parameters\n\n    @parameterized.expand(load_test_cases)\n    def test(self, test_name, nf_filter, nf_name, model_invariant_uuid, model_version_id, orchestration_status,\n             expected_result):\n            pass\n\n\n\n\nStrip out the base object and make the \"data\" array in the filter_test_data.json file be the root element.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 4023,
        "name": "Joseph O'Leary",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "joseph.o.leary@est.tech",
        "username": "JoeOLeary"
      },
      "updated": "2020-09-07 13:52:37.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
